Outline

In this course, we review some of the fundamentals of machine learning (ML) with Caret and R. Topics covered include:

  • Exploratory data analysis
  • Data pre-processing
  • Machine learning models: Random Forest and Linear Discriminant Analysis
  • Model comparison

And the question now is the following: What is Machine Learning? Firstly, a hot topic in the last years. Generally speaking, a system that can access data and use it to learn and extract underlying knowledge from it in order to automatically learn without being explicitly programmed for it. So, it learns from your data (handle with care), its fast and it tends to overfits to your data (handle with care). So we are able to build a model on the data and then use it to predict on new data. They learn patterns from the data so a particular pattern not present in your data could not been predicted nor even known by the model. Furthermore, the big assumption here is that what we learn from the past will be used to predict the future and as we know, the future in unpredictable. So handle with care following a good experimental design to reduce the uncertainties.

A ML is said to overfit if the algoritms is more accurate predicting/fitting to known data (used in the training of the algorithm) than in predicting with new unknown data. A good generalization capability is thus desired. We will cover some tasks for a proper experimental design in classification problems despite the fact that there are other problems in ML research such as: regression, survival, clustering and much more. A methodology for the design of experiments with regression models is available open access here.

Caret

Nowadays one of the strenghts in ML research is that you can search for a particular algorithm in a particular programming language and youll have several different implemenations. Even more, if you need to build a ML model youll have several differnt robust methodologies. At the same time, the big drawback is that everything is here and YOU must handle it with care. Otherways youll build a bad model with a poor prediction and generalization capability. This means problems!

One of the biggest efforts to normalize, democratize and standardize ML using R is the Caret package, a bookdown here. Developed by Max Kuhn, is a single interface to hundred or thousands of functions through a complex ML pipeline. The caret package (short for Classification And Regression Training) contains tools for:

  • data splitting
  • pre-processing
  • feature selection
  • model tuning
  • variable importance
  • and much more functionalities

Following the caret documentation suggestion, in order to install the package execute the following package to ensure that all needed packages are installed and resolve all the dependencies:

install.packages("caret", dependencies = c("Depends", "Suggests"))

Be patient, it may take a while!

TCGA - BRCA dataset

Following the same steps that we used in the previous course we will download the TCGA-BRCA and in particular: transcriptome profiling of gene expression quantification where the experimental strategy is (RNAseq) and the workflow type is HTSeq-FPKM-UQ and only primary solid tumor data of the affymetrix GPL86 profile.

query = GDCquery(project = 'TCGA-BRCA', 
         data.category = 'Transcriptome Profiling',
         data.type = 'Gene Expression Quantification',
         experimental.strategy = 'RNA-Seq',
         workflow.type = 'HTSeq - FPKM-UQ')

GDCdownload(query)

brca.expDat = GDCprepare(query = query,
                    save = T,
                    save.filename = "TCGA-BRCA-RNASeq",
                    remove.files.prepared =  TRUE)

brca.omics = assay(brca.expDat)
brca.omics = as.data.frame(t(brca.omics))

samples = colData(brca.expDat)
rownames(samples) = 1:nrow(samples)
ptSamples = samples[which(samples$definition == 'Primary solid Tumor'), ]

ptSamples = ptSamples[, c('barcode', 'patient', 'vital_status', 'days_to_last_follow_up', 'days_to_death', 'gender', 'age_at_diagnosis','ajcc_pathologic_stage',
                          'tumor_stage','ajcc_pathologic_n','tumor_grade')]

mart <- useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl", useMart("ensembl"))
convert <- getBM(filters= c('ensembl_gene_id'), 
                 attributes= c('ensembl_gene_id', 'gene_biotype'),
                 values=names(brca.omics),
                 mart= mart)
protCod = convert[which(convert$gene_biotype == 'protein_coding'), ]
protCodIDs = protCod$ensembl_gene_id
brca.omics = brca.omics[, match(protCodIDs, names(brca.omics))]

platID96 = 'GPL96'

gpl96 = getGEO(platID96)

gpl96 = gpl96@dataTable@table
annot96 = gpl96[, c('ID', 'Gene Symbol', 'Gene Title', 'ENTREZ_GENE_ID')]

dict96 = getBM(filters= c('affy_hg_u133a'), 
               attributes= c('ensembl_gene_id', 'affy_hg_u133a','hgnc_symbol'),
               values= annot96$ID,
               mart= mart)

genes96 = unique(dict96$ensembl_gene_id)
brca.omics.96 = brca.omics[, intersect(names(brca.omics), genes96)]

colnames(brca.omics.96)<- dict96$hgnc_symbol[match(colnames(brca.omics.96),dict96$ensembl_gene_id)]

NOTE: Files brca.omics.96 and ptSamples are available for download from the Universidade da Coruas community in Zenodo here. Load them in R using the readRDS() function.

brca.omics.96<-readRDS(file = '~/Downloads/TCGA.BRCA.brca.omics.96.RData')
ptSamples <- readRDS(file = '~/Downloads/TCGA.BRCA.ptSamples.RData')

Exploratory data analysis

Before training any ML model its important to understand your data. Thus, an initial descriptive exploratory analysis is of interest. For exaple, some typical errors arise during the loading process of the data. Furthermore, sometimes codification problems such as slash, values of 0 for unknown data or other similar situations.

Features types.

One of the initial steps should be the check of the types of the features in order to check that all numeric values are numbers for R and that cualitative features are factor or boolean for example. You can do this task with str() from base or glimpse from Tibble for example:

Train and test dataset

In order to evaluate the predictive power of the ML we must ensure that the models performance should be equal (or close to) with unknown new patients. In orther to do this, well separate the dataset in two groups: training and test (80-20%) according with the output. Furthermore, this dataset has a FPKM normalization (reads/fragments per kilobase of exon per million reads/fragments mapped) but most of the ML models are sensible to differences in the scale of the features so, there are mainly two different approaches: normalization or standardization. Generally speaking, standardization (scale the features to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1) is preferred. In R we have the scale() function. This step belongs to the next section (data preprocessing) but its preferable to do it before data splitting.

brca.data <- as.data.frame(scale(brca.omics.96))
mean(brca.data$TP53)

brca.data$output <- ptSamples[match(row.names(brca.data),ptSamples$barcode),"age_at_diagnosis.fac"]
brca.data <- brca.data %>% drop_na(output)

Data preprocessing

Caret has several different useful functions for all the steps of a ML analysis pipeline. One of them is nearZeroVar() to remove those features with a single value (zero-variance) because they are useless.

nzv <- nearZeroVar(brca.data)
head(nzv)
## [1]  538 1324 1721 1833 1915 1944
length(nzv)
## [1] 251
brca.data.nzv <- brca.data[,-nzv]

By default, nearZeroVar will return the positions of the problematic features. We remove those features.

Most of the models may benefit from reducing the level of correlation between features. More correlation does not imply more information and, on the other hand, likely imply more noise. Caret has a findCorrelation() function for this task.

output <- brca.data.nzv %>% select('output')
data <- brca.data.nzv[,setdiff(colnames(brca.data.nzv),'output')]
high.cor <- findCorrelation(data, cutoff = .75)
## Warning in averageCorr[colsToCheck] > averageCorr[rowsToCheck]: longer object
## length is not a multiple of shorter object length
brca.data.nzv.cor <- brca.data.nzv[,-high.cor]
brca.data.nzv.cor$output <- output

A cutoff of .75 is clearly too much ;)

We will keep the final set of genes as the ones of interest so we must keep them too in the train and test datasets:

brca.data_train <- brca.data_train %>% select(names(brca.data.nzv.cor))
brca.data_test <- brca.data_test %>% select(names(brca.data.nzv.cor))

Machine Learning models: Random Forest and Linear Discriminant Analysis

In the following sections we will train and tune two ML models: Random Forest and Linear Discriminant Analysis and well compare them with the same train and test datasets.

Random Forest

Random forest (RF) combines several classification trees, which are fitted to subsamples of the original sample-set using randomly selected subsets of predictor variables. From the complete forest, a single global prediction is obtained as an average (in case of regression) or majority vote (in case of classification) of the prediction of all trees. The advantages of this method are: (1) it is simple and results are easy to interpret in the case of few predictors; and (2) it can be applied to many problems, even if there are high-order interaction effects or non-linear relationships between the variables. The ranger R package was used for the analysis. Well need more dependencies: e1071 REMEMBER: use Caret to rule them all!

In order to follow a robust experimental design well follow this approach with 5 runs of a 10-fold cross-validation approach. This particular implementation of the RF has the following hyperparameters:

  • mtry: number of features randomly selected for each tree. Well test with the following range: 3, 5, 7.
  • min.node.size: minimum nodes size to be divided. Well test with the following range: 2, 4, 6.
  • splitrule: division criteria.

Furthermore, hyperparameter tuning could be expensive in terms of computational power. In order to increase the speed of working well use a package for paralelization (without coding especifically nothing!) called doParallel. Remember to install.packages('doParallel').

library(doParallel)
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loading required package: iterators
cl <- makePSOCKcluster(3)
registerDoParallel(cl)

cv.k  <- 10
reps <- 5

hyperparameters <- expand.grid(mtry = c(3, 5, 7),
                               min.node.size = c(2, 4, 6),
                               splitrule = "gini")

set.seed(1234)
seeds <- vector(mode = "list", length = (cv.k * reps) + 1)
for (i in 1:(cv.k * reps)) {
  seeds[[i]] <- sample.int(1000, nrow(hyperparameters))
}
seeds[[(cv.k * reps) + 1]] <- sample.int(1000, 1)

train.control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = cv.k,
                              repeats = reps, seeds = seeds,
                              returnResamp = "final", verboseIter = TRUE,
                              allowParallel = TRUE)

set.seed(5678)
rf.model <- train(x = brca.data_train[,-ncol(brca.data_train)],
                  y= brca.data_train$output,
                  method = "ranger",
                  tuneGrid = hyperparameters,
                  metric = "Accuracy",
                  importance= 'impurity',
                  trControl = train.control,
                  num.trees = 500)
## Aggregating results
## Selecting tuning parameters
## Fitting mtry = 7, splitrule = gini, min.node.size = 2 on full training set

Linear Discriminant Analysis

One of the most used baseline ML models is Linear Discriminant Analaysi (LDA). Remember the Occams razor, the simplest explanation is usually the right one: less features, less hyperparameters, less complexity and so on. There is not an absolutely better ML model for every single possible task so we should always run several different experiments with several models in order to understand and explore our problem from different points of view.

In order to follow a robust experimental design well follow again this approach with 5 runs of a 10-fold cross-validation approach.

This particular implementation of the LDA has no hyperparameters so it fits perfectly the baseline model definition.

set.seed(5678)
lda.model <- train(output ~ ., data = brca.data_train,
                   method = "lda",
                   metric = "Accuracy",
                   trControl = train.control)
## Aggregating results
## Fitting final model on full training set
lda.model

In this case, we are going to compare a complex model with three hyperparameters such as RF against a simple baseline model without hyperparameters such as LDA.

Model comparison

After the experiments we have two ML models, trained in the same conditions and with the same experimental design so now, the question is, which is the best one?

We ran 5 repetitions of a 10-fold cross-validation experiment using set.seed() to ensure that both models worked on the same set of data and partitions and in the same order. With resamples() we can extract performance metrics for each repetition.

results <- list(RF=rf.model, LDA=lda.model)
resam.results <- resamples(results)
resam.results$values %>% head()
bwplot(resam.results)

Lets check if we have one of the models that provide better performance in terms of accuracy:

xyplot(resam.results, metric = "Accuracy")

dotplot(resam.results, metric = "Accuracy")

And finally a density plot to look for outlier folds with unusual high or low values of accuracy:

densityplot(resam.results, metric = "Accuracy")

At this point, a good idea is to plot the results using ggplot and for this, we should change the data.frame to something more friedly as we did before:

resam.results.gg <- resam.results$values %>%
                         gather(key = "model", value = "value", -Resample) %>%
                         separate(col = "model", into = c("model", "score"),
                                  sep = "~", remove = TRUE)
resam.results.gg %>% head()

Lets check the behaviour of the models during the five runs:

resam.results.gg %>% 
  group_by(model, score) %>% 
  summarise(mean.5run = mean(value)) %>%
  spread(key = score, value = mean.5run) %>%
  arrange(desc(Accuracy))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'model' (override with `.groups` argument)

This is the training error of 5 runs of a 10-fold CV, which is a good estimator, however we have a subset of unknown patients for the models and we want to check the real generalization capability of the models. Well use the extractPrediction() function that, according to the Rdocumentation will calculate the training and test data predictions. The original training data are used to predict on.

preds.results <- extractPrediction(
                  models = results,
                  testX = brca.data_test %>% select(-output),
                  testY = brca.data_test$output
                )
## Warning in predict.lda(modelFit, newdata): variable names in 'newdata' do not
## match those in 'object'

## Warning in predict.lda(modelFit, newdata): variable names in 'newdata' do not
## match those in 'object'
preds.results %>% head()
preds.scores <- preds.results %>%
                         mutate(success = ifelse(obs == pred, TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
                         group_by(object, dataType) %>%
                         summarise(accuracy = mean(success))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'object' (override with `.groups` argument)
preds.scores %>%
  spread(key = dataType, value = accuracy) %>%
  arrange(desc(Test))

Open questions

  1. Are the important genes related with the biological condition?
  2. Training errors close to 1 and test errors much lower means something?
  3. According to the results could we improve the RF?
  4. Why the OOB error is so similar to the CV error?
  5. Are accuracy and kappa good performance measures for binary problems?
  6. Can we extract conclusions from age at diagnosis binary divided into early and late?
  7. Can we extract genetic conclusions from age at diagnosis?
  8. Is a good idea to have imbalanced data?
  9. What is missing to do a real cancer analysis using ML, R and Caret?
  10. Moving from more 12,000 genes to more than 600 is a huge jump, isnt?
  11. Can you use feature selection or feature extraction techniques to reduce the dimensionality of the problem?
  12. Can we learn something from the ML results in train and test? What does this kappa means? Is a better measure than accuracy?
  13. Where do we have to go to check info from a gen?
  14. Gens arent alone in the genome, they use to work together. Were do we have to go to check info from pathways?
